	<section xml:id="review">
		<title>Review</title>


		<subsection xml:id="complex-numbers-aleks-r6">
			<title>Complex Numbers (ALEKS R.6)</title>

			<p>
				One property of any given real number is that its square is always nonnegative. That is, there is no real number <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 = -1</m>. To remedy this situation, we introduce a new number called an imaginary unit.
			</p>

<!-- div attr= class="ColoredDefinition"-->
			<p>
				Imaginary Unitdef:imaginary-unit The <term>imaginary unit</term>, <m>i</m>, is defined to be a solution to the equation <m>x^2 = -1</m>. The solution set for the equation <m>x^2=-1</m> is <m>\{i,-i\}</m>, where <m>i</m> is the <term>principal square root</term> of <m>-1</m>. Thus, <m>i^2=-1</m> by definition, and we use the notation <m>i = \sqrt{-1}</m>.
			</p><!--</div attr= class="ColoredDefinition">-->

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
			<p>
				<term>Example 1.1</term>.  <em>Simplify the following.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(2) <m>\sqrt{-12}</m> <m>-\sqrt{-25}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

<!-- div attr= class="objectivebox"-->
			<p>
				Simplifying imaginary numbers The powers of <m>i</m> repeat with every fourth power. Even powers of <m>i</m> result in <m>1</m> or <m>-1</m>, whereas odd powers of <m>i</m> result in <m>i</m> or <m>-i</m>.
			</p><!--</div attr= class="objectivebox">-->

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
			<p>
				<term>Example 1.1</term>.  <em>Simplify the given powers of <m>i</m>.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(2) <m>i^{3}</m> <m>i^{4}</m> <m>i^{5}</m> <m>i^{6}</m> <m>i^{103}</m> <m>i^{-30}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

<!-- div attr= class="ColoredDefinition"-->
			<p>
				Complex Numberdef:complex-number The <term>standard form</term> of a <term>complex number</term> is <m>a+bi</m>, where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers. The value <m>a</m> is called the <term>real part</term> and the value <m>b</m> is called the <term>imaginary part</term>.
			</p><!--</div attr= class="ColoredDefinition">-->

<!-- div attr= class="objectivebox"-->
			<p>
				Operations with complex numbers Addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division of complex numbers follows a natural set of rules, as discussed below.
			</p><!--</div attr= class="objectivebox">-->

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
			<p>
				<term>Example 1.1</term>.  <em>Write the following numbers in standard <m>a + bi</m> form.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(2) <m>4i-(3+2i)+(1-3i)</m> <m>(4+2i)(3-i)</m>
			</p>

			<p>
				<m>(3 + 4i)^{2}</m> <m>\sqrt{-3}\cdot\sqrt{-12}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

<!-- div attr= class="ColoredDefinition"-->
			<p>
				Complex Conjugatedef:complex-conjugate The <term>complex conjugate</term> of <m>z=a+bi</m> is <m>\overline{z} =a-bi</m>. Notice that the product of conjugates is a real number. In particular,
			</p>

<!-- div attr= class="center"-->
			<p>
				<m>z\overline{z}=(a+bi)(a-bi)</m> = .
			</p><!--</div attr= class="center">--><!--</div attr= class="ColoredDefinition">-->

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
			<p>
				<term>Example 1.1</term>.  <em>Divide the following complex numbers and write answer in <m>a+bi</m> form.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(2) <m>\displaystyle{4+2i\over 3-i}</m> <m>\displaystyle{4\over 3+5i}</m> <m>\displaystyle{\sqrt{-24}\over \sqrt{-8}}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

			<p>
				<term>Students - Check your understanding</term>
			</p>

<!-- div attr= class="checkyourunderstanding"-->
			<p>
				<term>CYU 1.1</term>.  <em>Write down the following as a complex number in its standard form. Leave no negative numbers under radicals and no radicals in denominator.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="checkyourunderstanding">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(3) <m>-\sqrt{-17}</m> <m>\sqrt{-5}\cdot\sqrt{-20}</m> <m>\displaystyle\frac{\sqrt{-81}}{\sqrt{3}}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

<!-- div attr= class="checkyourunderstanding"-->
			<p>
				<term>CYU 1.2</term>.  <em>Simplify the following powers of <m>i</m>.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="checkyourunderstanding">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(3) <m>i^{48}</m> <m>i^{23}</m> <m>i^{-19}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

<!-- div attr= class="checkyourunderstanding"-->
			<p>
				<term>CYU 1.3</term>.  <em>Perform the indicated operations. Write answer in <m>a+bi</m> form.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="checkyourunderstanding">-->

<!-- div attr= class="tasks"-->
			<p>
				(1) <m>\left( 8-3i\right) -\left( 2+4i\right) +\left( 5+7i\right)</m> <m>\left( -5+4i\right) \left( 3-i\right)</m> <m>\left( 10-3i\right) \left( 10+3i\right)</m> <m>\displaystyle\frac{5+6i}{2-7i}</m>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="tasks">-->

<!-- div attr= class="objectivebox"-->
			<p>
				Solving polynomials over the set of complex numbers The quadratic equation <m>ax^2+bx+c=0</m> has either one or two unique solution(s), given by <me>\displaystyle x={-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}\over 2a}.</me> Solving higher order polynomials involves other techniques (see Chapter 2). For instance, the expressions representing the sum and difference of two cubes can be factored as follows: <me>\begin{align*}
    a^3 + b^3 &amp; = (a + b)(a^2 - ab + b^2) \\
    a^3 - b^3 &amp; = (a - b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)
\end{align*}</me>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="objectivebox">-->

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
			<p>
				<term>Example 1.1</term>.  <em>Find all complex zeros of <m>f(x) = x^4+27x</m>.</em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
			<p>
				<term>Example 1.1</term>.  <em>Solve <m>(2x+5)^{2} - 7(2x+5) - 30 = 0</m></em>
			</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

<!-- div attr= class="ColoredDefinition"-->
			<p>
